The molecular interaction of a fluorophore (donor) with a quencher (acceptor) results in quenching of fluorescence and quantum yield reduction. Fig. 7 a shows the decrease in PL intensity, i.e., turn-off fluorescence, upon addition of PA from 0 μM to 200 μM in the GQD-50 solution. GQD-30 and GQD-110 did not show a significant reduction in PL intensity. The type of fluorescence quenching gives an idea about the mechanism of energy transfer. Fluorescence quenching may be either static or dynamic depending on their interaction in the ground state via complex formation or collision in the excited state, respectively (Chakraborti et al., 2013). This can be predicted by performing the TRPL analysis. The fluorescence lifetime analysis of GQD-50 was performed after the addition of PA and compared with nascent GQD-50 (Fig. 7b). The average fluorophore lifetime of GQD-50 before and after PA addition was found to be ca. 4.5 ns, which are almost similar, anticipating static quenching (Chakraborti et al., 2013; Wang et al., 2014a, b). PA addition resulted in a reduction of the short (
τ 1
) as well as long (
τ 2
τ 3
) lifetime components of GQD-50 (Table S2). This predicts band-band electronic transition and surface functionalities are responsible for the fluorophore-quencher complex formation, respectively (Chakraborti et al., 2013).
